The optical absorption properties of materials were examined using UV–vis diffuse reflectance absorption spectroscopy (DRS). The absorption edge of pure Bi2MoO6 was noted at around 470 nm, as shown in Fig. 7
                     a. With varying composite ratios of BPB/Bi2MoO6, the absorption edges displayed a red-shift towards longer wavelengths and exhibited increased absorption within the 500–800 nm range, implying a narrowed band gap. This suggests that by incorporating BPB in BPB/Bi2MoO6 composites, there is a significant enhancement in their light harvesting efficiency. Consequently, these composites have the potential to capture more light, thereby generating a higher number of electron-hole pairs and subsequently boosting their photocatalytic activity when exposed to visible light. The band gap of the samples prepared was evaluated using the Kubelka-Munk function, also known as the Tauc plot method, with the equation (αhν)n = A(hν-E
                     g). Here, α represents the material's light absorption coefficient, ν signifies the optical frequency, h denotes the Planck constant, and A is the absorption constant. The plots of (αhν)2 versus hν are depicted in Fig. 7b. The band gaps of BPB/Bi2MoO6 at various composite ratios were found to be lower than pristine Bi2MoO6, with values of 2.74 eV and 2.46 eV for Bi2MoO6 and BPB/Bi2MoO6 (1:4) respectively. The Mott-Schottky test was conducted to Bi2MoO6 and BPB/Bi2MoO6 (1:4) to determine the flat-band potential (Efb
                     ) values, revealing n-type semiconductor behavior with Efb values of −0.22 eV and −0.01 eV (Ag/AgCl, pH = 7), respectively (Fig. S4). Considering the standard hydrogen electrode potential (ENHE = EAg/AgCl + 0.197), the calculated Efb
                      value for Bi2MoO6 and BPB/Bi2MoO6 (1:4) were −0.02 eV and 0.19 eV (NHE, pH = 7) [60]. Typically, the Efb
                      is approximately 0.2 eV lower than the conduction band potential (ECB
                     ) for n-type semiconductors, resulting in ECB
                      values of −0.22 eV and −0.01 eV (vs. NHE) for Bi2MoO6 and BPB/Bi2MoO6 (1:4) [15], respectively. According to the empirical formula (Eg = EVB-ECB
                     ), the valance band potential (EVB
                     ) values of Bi2MoO6 and BPB/Bi2MoO6 (1:4) were calculated to be 2.52 eV and 2.45 eV (vs. NHE), respectively, which were consistent with the valence band XPS results (Fig. 7c). These measurements and calculations aided in estimating the band structure as shown in Fig. 7d.
